          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Investment Visa (Entrepreneur)</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-700">
            <li>Business capital: <strong>Varies (HK$500K-5M typical)</strong></li>
            <li>Company setup: <strong>HK$5,000</strong></li>
            <li>Office (annual, Kowloon): <strong>HK$300,000-600,000</strong></li>
            <li>Visa/admin fees: <strong>HK$5,000</strong></li>
            <li>Legal/consulting: <strong>HK$30,000-80,000</strong></li>
            <li>Insurance (annual): <strong>HK$30,000-60,000</strong></li>
            <li class="pt-2 border-t font-semibold">Year 1 total: <strong>HK$870,000-5,750,000+</strong></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Living Costs in Hong Kong</h3>

    <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-blue-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Housing</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The major expense. A 500 sq ft apartment: HK$20,000-40,000/month (outside Central). Central/Mid-Levels: HK$35,000-70,000+. Family-sized apartments (1000+ sq ft): HK$50,000-150,000. Deposits typically 2 months.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-green-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">International Schools</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">If you have children, international school fees are substantial: HK$100,000-250,000/year per child, plus debentures (HK$500,000-2,000,000 often required). Local schools are much cheaper but may not suit non-Chinese speakers.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-purple-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Daily Life</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Dining out is reasonable (local food HK$50-100/meal, Western HK$150-400). Transportation is efficient and affordable (MTR, buses). Groceries at international supermarkets are expensive; local markets are cheaper.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-4 mt-6">
      <p class="text-green-800">
        <strong>Tax advantage:</strong> Hong Kong's simple tax system (15% max, no capital gains, territorial basis) can offset high living costs for many investors. No VAT/GST. If your income derives from outside Hong Kong, it may not be taxable at all under territorial taxation rules.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Application Process -->
  <section id="application" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Application Process</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Hong Kong's visa applications are processed by the Immigration Department. Processing is generally efficient—4-8 weeks for most applications. You can apply from abroad or within Hong Kong (if on a valid stay).
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={timelineColumns} rows={timelineRows} />

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-8 mb-3">Step-by-Step Guide (Investment Visa)</h3>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">1</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Develop Business Plan</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Create a comprehensive business plan for your Hong Kong operations. Include: business concept, market analysis, financial projections, staffing plans, and your relevant background. Immigration assesses whether your business contributes to Hong Kong's economy.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">2</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Register Hong Kong Company</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Incorporate your company with the Companies Registry. Quick and affordable—can be done online or through company secretarial services. Obtain Business Registration Certificate. Consider using a registered office address if you don't have premises yet.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">3</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Gather Required Documents</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Prepare: passport, photos, company registration documents, business plan, proof of capital, CV/resume, academic certificates, evidence of business experience, office lease (if available), and letter explaining your business intentions.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">4</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Submit Application</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Submit to Immigration Department—online, by mail, or in person at Immigration Tower, Wan Chai. Pay HK$230 fee. Applications from abroad go through Chinese embassy/consulate or can be submitted by Hong Kong representative.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">5</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Processing and Follow-up</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Immigration reviews your application (4-8 weeks typically). They may request additional documents or clarification. Respond promptly to any queries. You may be called for interview, though this isn't common for straightforward cases.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">6</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Receive Approval and Entry</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Upon approval, you receive a visa label or electronic visa. Enter Hong Kong within validity period. If applying from abroad, affix visa to passport at embassy. Initial stay is typically 1-2 years for business-related visas.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">7</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Register for HKID</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Within 30 days of arrival, register for Hong Kong Identity Card at Registration of Persons offices. The HKID is essential for banking, healthcare, and daily life. Carry it at all times (legal requirement).</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">8</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Maintain Status and Renew</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Continue operating your business successfully. Apply for extension before visa expires. Pattern: 1-2-2-3 years. After 7 years continuous ordinary residence, apply for permanent resident status (Right of Abode).</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 mt-6">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>CIES application note:</strong> The Capital Investment Entrant Scheme has additional requirements—must work with an approved financial intermediary, investments must be properly documented, and there are specific timelines for deploying capital. Consult with CIES specialists for detailed guidance.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

