        <strong>Emergency care:</strong> For true emergencies, public hospital A&E departments provide excellent care without the wait times affecting specialist clinics. Call 999 for ambulance. Many expats use public A&E for emergencies, then transfer to private for follow-up care.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I get Hong Kong citizenship?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. Hong Kong does not offer citizenship—it's a Special Administrative Region of China. After 7 years continuous ordinary residence, you can apply for Permanent Resident status (Right of Abode), which provides most benefits of citizenship: no visa restrictions, voting rights in some elections, and security of tenure. PR is the endpoint of the immigration journey.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What counts as "continuous residence" for PR?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          You must ordinarily reside in Hong Kong for 7 continuous years. Brief trips abroad are fine, but extended absences may break continuity. General guidance: maintain your home in HK, keep your HKID active, and don't establish primary residence elsewhere. Each case is assessed individually—there's no hard rule on days abroad.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is residential property really excluded from CIES?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. The 2024 CIES specifically excludes residential property from the HK$30M investment. This is different from the pre-2015 scheme which allowed property. You can buy residential property personally, but it doesn't count toward immigration requirements. Non-residential property (commercial/industrial) may partially qualify within limits.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can my spouse work in Hong Kong?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Spouses of visa holders can apply for Dependent visa with unrestricted work rights. They can work for any employer or start their own business without changing visa status. Children on Dependent visas can study but cannot work until age 18.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What if my business fails?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Your visa status depends on maintaining valid purpose. If your business closes, you'd need to find employment (change to employment visa), start a new business, or leave Hong Kong. Discuss contingency plans with immigration advisors. Having PR (after 7 years) provides security—you can stay regardless of employment status.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How has Hong Kong changed since 2019?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Hong Kong has changed significantly. The National Security Law (2020) altered the political and legal landscape. Some businesses have relocated; others have expanded. For investors, the fundamentals remain: low tax, rule of law for commercial matters, China access, and financial infrastructure. Make your own assessment based on your business needs and risk tolerance.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Hong Kong remains a premier destination for investors and entrepreneurs seeking Asian exposure, tax efficiency, and world-class financial infrastructure. The CIES (HK$30M) is among the most expensive passive investment visa programs globally, but provides access to a sophisticated financial center. The Investment Visa offers a more accessible route for genuine entrepreneurs with viable Hong Kong businesses.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The trade-offs are real: extremely high living costs, uncertain political evolution, and no path to citizenship. Hong Kong offers Permanent Residence after 7 years—valuable, but different from citizenship available in Japan or Europe. The healthcare system requires private insurance for practical access, adding to costs.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      For investors who prioritize tax efficiency (zero capital gains, 15% max income), China access, English-speaking environment, and Asian financial hub status, Hong Kong delivers unique value. Understand the costs, plan for comprehensive health insurance, and make an informed decision about whether Hong Kong's advantages align with your priorities.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        Hong Kong suits investors and entrepreneurs who prioritize tax efficiency, China access, and Asian financial hub benefits over citizenship pathways and lower living costs. Come with realistic expectations about costs (housing, schools, insurance), a genuine business rationale, and understanding of the current environment. For the right profile, Hong Kong offers unmatched advantages in Asia.
      </p>
